# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-storm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] A Storm application is designed as a "topology" in the shape of a directed acyclic graph (DAG) with spouts and bolts acting as the graph vertices.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Edges on the graph are named streams and direct data from one node to another.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Together, the topology acts as a data transformation pipeline.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] At a superficial level the general topology structure is similar to a MapReduce job, with the main difference being that data is processed in real time as opposed to in individual batches.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Additionally, Storm topologies run indefinitely until killed, while a MapReduce job DAG must eventually end.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Storm became an Apache Top-Level Project in September 2014 and was previously in incubation since September 2013.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Apache Storm is developed under the Apache License, making it available to most companies to use.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Git is used for version control and Atlassian Jira for issue tracking, under the Apache Incubator program.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Storm is but one of dozens of stream processing engines, for a more complete list see Stream processing.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] Twitter announced Heron on June 2, 2015 which is API compatible with Storm.
[src:apache-storm/apache-storm] There are other comparable streaming data engines such as Spark Streaming and Flink.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] In connection-oriented communication, a **data stream** is the transmission of a sequence of digitally encoded signals to convey information.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Typically, the transmitted symbols are grouped into a series of packets.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Most data transmitted over the Internet is transmitted as a data stream.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Using a mobile phone to have a conversation transmits the sound as a data stream.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] 2. $\Delta$ is a sequence of positive real time intervals.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Data Stream contains different sets of data, that depend on the chosen data format.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] A **data point** is a tag that collects information about a certain action, performed by a user on a website.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Data points exists in two types, the values of which are used to create appropriate audiences.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Information gathered out of websites are based on user behavior.
[src:apache-storm/data-stream] Data providers deliver both personal or non-personal information.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:apache-storm/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:apache-storm/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
