[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] In computer science, **stream processing** (also known as **event stream processing**, **data stream processing**, or **distributed stream processing**) is a programming paradigm which views streams, or sequences of events in time, as the central input and output objects of computation.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Stream processing encompasses dataflow programming, reactive programming, and distributed data processing.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Stream processing systems use streaming algorithms to trace parallel processing for data streams.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] The stream processing paradigm simplifies parallel software and hardware by restricting the parallel computation that can be performed.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Given a sequence of data (a *stream*), a series of operations (*kernel functions*) is applied to each element in the stream.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Kernel functions are usually pipelined, and optimal local on-chip memory reuse is attempted, in order to minimize the loss in bandwidth, associated with external memory interaction.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] *Uniform streaming*, where one kernel function is applied to all elements in the stream, is typical.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Since the kernel and stream abstractions expose data dependencies, compiler tools can fully automate and optimize on-chip management tasks.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Stream processing hardware can use scoreboarding, for example, to initiate a direct memory access (DMA) when dependencies become known.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] The elimination of manual DMA management reduces software complexity, and an associated elimination for hardware cached I/O, reduces the data area expanse that has to be involved with service by specialized computational units such as arithmetic logic units.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] During the 1980s stream processing was explored within dataflow programming.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] An example is the language SISAL (Streams and Iteration in a Single Assignment Language).
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Stream processing is essentially a compromise, driven by a data-centric model that works very well for traditional DSP or GPU-type applications (such as image, video and digital signal processing) but less so for general purpose processing with more randomized data access (such as databases).
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] By sacrificing some flexibility in the model, the implications allow easier, faster and more efficient execution.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] Depending on the context, processor design may be tuned for maximum efficiency or a trade-off for flexibility.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] For each record we can only read from the input, perform operations on it, and write to the output.
[src:apache-storm/stream-processing] It is permissible to have multiple inputs and multiple outputs, but never a piece of memory that is both readable and writable.
